Observation Details: Rare this far south. This yearn a big push of black capped chickadee south has been happening in cuyahoga county and other counties around the great lakes and in the Midwest. The last two days of good north winds have pushed lots of new birds in and  I suspect this bird may have moved in with everything else. I picked up on the Black capped vocalization. Visually white on the greater coverts and secondaries. Olive color in back, more colorful then Carolina. Lower bib line somewhat sloppy and clean.  The bird responded immediately to black capped calls.and flew right in for better photos. Typically from my experience Carolina’s don’t come in to black capped calls. and continue doing what they are doing or actually fly away. I seeked a second opinion from two Ohio ebird reviewers,both agreed  looks good for black cape so I’m submitting this as black capped chickadee.

Observation Details: *High; careful count throughout the day. Really low for amount of area we covered.
Entered nest in tree cavity with food several times. Left nest with fecal sac. I peeked in and managed to get a view of at least three chicks.

I was trying to find good riparian habitat along the Cowichan River and drove to the hatchery, which was gated and signs indicate access is not permitted. I had the windows down and heard a song near the gate that sounded bang on for Black-capped Chickadee. I stopped the car, stepped out, and the bird continued to sing repeatedly, confirming it was not just some off notes in the song of a regular species. At this point, I recorded the song on my phone and proceeded to get views to confirm the identification. I then retrieved my camera and got some decent photos to go with the recording. The first confirmed Vancouver Island record of Black-capped Chickadee from Island View Regional Park - in the area from at least August 20, 2021 to May 1, 2022 - pertained to an individual that was surprisingly shy. The one at the hatchery was very vocal and conspicuous, which leads me to suspect this is not the same individual. Subsequent efforts to relocate the bird have been unsuccessful.

Bold, contrasting colors; buffy flanks; substantial white edges on the greater coverts, the secondaries, and the outer tail feathers; clean border of the white cheeks and gray back; and chick-a-dee-dee call lower and slower than local Carolina Chickadees.

Observation Details: Continuing bird found by Gene;  Identified  by extensive white edges on the greater coverts and secondaries forming the classic “hockey stick” look; black tertials contrasting with grayish back and white-edged secondaries; greenish-gray back; very white cheek extending well onto the nape; bib a little messy and especially note the bulge at lower corners giving it a less triangular look; head looks largish; buffy sides seem brighter and extend further up than typical Carolina. Seemed less skittish than the Carolinas visiting the same area. This bird appears to have one lame foot and is missing several tail feathers on one side (perhaps it survived a predator attack).  First documented Lynchburg city record. #204 on my city list.

Observation Details: I was trying to find good riparian habitat along the Cowichan River and drove to the hatchery, which was gated and signs indicate access is not permitted. I had the windows down and heard a song near the gate that sounded bang on for Black-capped Chickadee. I stopped the car, stepped out, and the bird continued to sing repeatedly, confirming it was not just some off notes in the song of a regular species. At this point, I recorded the song on my phone and proceeded to get views to confirm the identification. I then retrieved my camera and got some decent photos to go with the recording. The first confirmed Vancouver Island record of Black-capped Chickadee from Island View Regional Park - in the area from at least August 20, 2021 to May 1, 2022 - pertained to an individual that was surprisingly shy. The one at the hatchery was very vocal and conspicuous, which leads me to suspect this is not the same individual. Subsequent efforts to relocate the bird have been unsuccessful.

Observation Details: Minimum exact count, including at least 3 singing "fe-be." Heard high-pitched calls from chickadees near the E property boundary along the stream at 0927, at which point I noticed the falcon was gone from its perch. Between this time and ca 0945, observed lots of activity from at least 7 chickadees in this area, including quite a bit of social behavior, with 2 to 5 birds flying around and flitting from perch to perch in a close area. This seemed to include some chases and displacement of birds from perches. For a few minutes around 0948 the chickadees in this area were very quiet, while I heard magpies calling a lot from downstream. Wondered if a predator was around but if so did not find it. At 0952, observed an apparent aggressive chase between 2 individuals in the E part of reach 4, with one close behind the other for ca 10 m. Immediate after, I heard high, soft "se-se-se" calls (different from the high se-se-se predator alarm calls) dropping into a gargle from one of the two - not sure which one. Heard at least 2 of the chickadee group as far upstream as the red culvert. Later, heard a BCCH singing between the diversion and the rocky draw, then observed it foraging near me and got photos and a recording. Wondered if it was perhaps another in addition to the previous 7, but later sightings suggested to me that I could not be sure of that. The snow depth where I observed it along the N bank of the creek was about 57 cm; this chickadee appeared to be solitary, as with the sightings on 7 Mar. Ca 1300, I heard and saw 1 BCCH in the vicinity of the cross-fence, singing and making "de-de-de" calls, only after I had passed by it. Later, I heard at least 2 chickadees near the turnaround, 1 singing. On the return I encountered 2 BCCH at the diversion.

Media notes: Leucistic Black-capped Chickadee.
Observation Details: Fewer than usual, but (per the pictures below) saw the coolest looking leucistic Black-capped Chickadee! I had seen an unusually white bird flitting around among some tall weeds and going into some evergreen trees next to the tall weeds, so went to investigate. Saw several normal Chickadees, and then spied the very white bird I had seen disappear into the evergreens. At first I thought it was a strange looking Snow Bunting (strange behaviour too, perching in a tree), but after reviewing the pictures, and sharing with an e-bird data quality volunteer for the area, we both concluded this was a leucistic Black-capped Chickadee. Note the beak, side view of the wings/flanks, tail length, and light but buffy underside - undoubtedly a Chickadee!

First looks showed more greenish than Carolina, larger headed, tawny flanks. Bib was ragged edged. I was trying to find good riparian habitat along the Cowichan River and drove to the hatchery, which was gated and signs indicate access is not permitted. I had the windows down and heard a song near the gate that sounded bang on for Black-capped Chickadee. I stopped the car, stepped out, and the bird continued to sing repeatedly, confirming it was not just some off notes in the song of a regular species. At this point, I recorded the song on my phone and proceeded to get views to confirm the identification. I then retrieved my camera and got some decent photos to go with the recording. The first confirmed Vancouver Island record of Black-capped Chickadee from Island View Regional Park - in the area from at least August 20, 2021 to May 1, 2022 - pertained to an individual that was surprisingly shy. The one at the hatchery was very vocal and conspicuous, which leads me to suspect this is not the same individual. Subsequent efforts to relocate the bird have been unsuccessful.
Singing BCCH song and richer call than CACH. Responded readily to playback and pics were taken showing the extensive white in the wingbars.
